# Context Engineering

Follow `docs/policy/context-engineering-policy.md` for prompts/tools. Follow `docs/policy/filesystem-context-policy.md` for the transcript, offloading, and compaction pipeline.

## Core Principles

- **Minimize tokens**: Find the smallest set of high-signal tokens that maximize outcomes.
- **Right altitude**: Balance brittle (prescriptive steps) vs. vague (generic guidance). Calibration test: would a senior engineer need this detail?
- **Single source of truth**: Tool description = HOW; system prompt = WHEN. Never explain the same concept twice.
- **Examples over rules**: One comprehensive example > three paragraphs of explanation.
- **Trust model capability**: If a competent developer wouldn't need the instruction, the model doesn't either.

## Filesystem Context Rules

- Transcripts: single append-only JSONL at `.tau/transcripts/{chatId}.jsonl`
- Every JSONL line has `role` + `timestamp`; content blocks split into separate lines
- Drop opaque data (signatures, indexes); skip tool_use blocks (captured by wrapToolCall)
- Tool offloading: large results to `.tau/tool-outputs/`, replaced with file path reference
- Skills/memory: loaded from `.tau/skills/` and `.tau/AGENTS.md` by middleware, never hardcoded in prompt
- All writes fire-and-forget (`void promise`) — never block the agent loop
- Compaction uses `append`, never `write` (overwrite)

## Prompt Anti-Patterns

| Anti-Pattern | Fix |
|---|---|
| Tool explained in prompt AND description | Keep in description only |
| "1. Analyze 2. Understand 3. Fix" | "Fix incrementally, verify after" |
| "CRITICAL: You MUST always..." | State once |
| All tool definitions in every request | Dynamic discovery |
| Full conversation history forever | Sliding windows + summarization |
| Signature/binary data in transcript | Drop — zero search value |
| `await` on transcript writes | `void` — fire-and-forget |
